I. Introduction

Cryptocurrencies have become a social phenomenon. There are prospects, as well as concerns surrounding the bitcoin fever. Some say cryptocurrencies are no less assets than stocks and bonds. Others say cryptocurrencies are mere gamble – that there are no fundamental values to them, and there is no sensible way to predict their prices.
One thing obvious, however, is that cryptocurrencies are actively being traded, even now, and involve quite some amount of money. Be it economically significant or not, there are room to make fortune out of it. Then, we want to predict their price. Especially, we want to know about Bitcoin, the most valuable and the most traded cryptocurrency. Let’s hope we can get some help from the neural network.


II. Method

1. Variables

1) Cryptocurrecy variable

We want to predict Bitcoin price. Obvious data are Bitcoin price, market capitalization and total volume. Despite the obvious relationship between these variables, \(Price \times Volume=Market Cap\), we are trying to predict, not necessarily interpret any of parameters. Also, considering Bitcoin’s unique background – that people mine, and that not all Bitcoin is traded immediately – there is ample reason to distinguish the volume from the price drive.

Other than the data about Bitcoin itself, we may consider including other cryptocurrencies, for they are interdependent, no less than traditional assets. For example, the recent rise of Dogecoin reignited the bitcoin fever. So, I gathered the prices of top 10 most traded cryptocurrencies as of November 2021: Ethereum, Binance, Tether, Cardano, Solana, Ripple, Polkadot, and Dogecoin.

Above are the time series plots of Bitcoin (Fig. 1) and other cryptocurrencies (Fig. 2). We can see several sudden surges. Not only Bitcoin, but other cryptocurrencies follow the similar trend. These surges might cause some problems, for they are often extreme and unexpectable.


2) Financial Variables

Cryptocurrencies are potentially substitutional to traditional assets such as stocks, bonds, and cash. Also, such assets reflect economic environments. For these reasons, I selected NASDAQ composite and S&P500; and U.S. treasury prices for 5-years (short term) and 10-years (long term).

Stock indexes are on increasing trend (Fig 3.). We can find the plunge from the COVID-19 incident, after which indexes continue to rise. Bond indexes, on the other hand, are relatively stable. But after the COVID-19 breakout, to vitalize economy, rates went down. They have been adjusting back to the rate before.


2. Neural network

Bitcoin price is a time series data. High autocorrelation is expected, especially because it’s largely driven by mass psychology. RNN seems suitable, then.
Meanwhile, we don’t want to reflect every old data in predicting today and tomorrow’s Bitcoin price. Bitcoin endured years of disinterest after its first introduction. We definitely don’t want to use those times’ data. After its major debut, Bitcoin price went through several soars and nosedives, each not really related. Investors act very short-sighted. We neither don’t want to reflect each of these fluctuations for too long. Then, LSTM method should come in handy.


III. Data Collection

Cryptocurrency data was collected using a free API CoinGecko , via API platform RapidAPI . The data is in form of time series, starting from 2013-04-28 on which the first data for Bitcoin is available, to 2021-11-20, when the data was collected. Other cryptocurrencies are traced starting from later than 2013-04-28. I replaced the NA’s with 0. Code used is stored in cryptocurrency_data.ipynb, and the collected data was exported to crypto.csv. The code may be used to reflect any newer data.
Stock indexes and U.S. treasury data were downloaded from NASDAQ homepage and Yahoo Finance homepage as .csv files. These data were modified and merged with cryptocurrency data using the code in full_data.ipynb, and was exported to data.csv.


IV. Code

1. Data preparation and RNN model

First, I scaled each variable to (0, 1) range for better performance. Then, the data were split into train and test set, each of proportion 0.7 and 0.3.
Next, I defined two functions: one (make_data()) for making the data form adequate for LSTM, another (run_rnn()) for running the neural network model. Inputs are train data, test data, k and l. Timestep parameter k indicates how many previous days to reflect, and l indicates the number of epochs.
The RNN model consists of 4 layers of LSTM and dropouts, with ordinary dense layer as output layer. Loss is defined with MSE.


2. Parameters

1) Epochs

I ran the model for 15 epochs as a start. For different timesteps, following learning curves were obtained (Fig. 4).
It seems the learning curves for the test data take upward turn at around 8th to 10th epoch, indicating possible overfitting. For the timestep of 360, the rebound happens earlier at around 5th epoch. So, I chose to use 10 as the number of epochs, except for when k=360 for which I will use 5 epochs.


2) Timestep

I tried 7 different timesteps and the results are presented in Figure 5 and Figure 6. If I only consider the loss rates, k = 30 is what I should choose. I indeed chose the value as the parameter, but there are other factors to consider other than MSE. I will elaborate the reason in the results.


V. Result/Conclusion

Below are the results for different k’s (Fig. 6). Actual and predicted prices are compared.

  1. Models generally fail to keep up with the stiff increases. Such lagging is not properly reflected in MSE. This is because the first half of test data is ranged before the sudden surges. LSTM method allows a model to adapt to this period. In effect, many models excel at predicting this period well, which drag down the MSE. However, we are more interested in predicting the latest trends. Thus, we should consider the predicting performance specifically in the latter half of the test data.
  1. Applying above criterion, timestep of 30 performs the best. I will use the model with k=30 to predict upcoming Bitcoin prices.
    Following is k=120 in terms of MSE, but not necessarily better than other cases. Overall, the longer the timestep, the model tends to make more smoothened predictions, resulting in worse performance.
  2. Meanwhile, I will have to look for parameters to adequately reflect the unpreceded fluctuations to models, or look for different models suitable for such unstable data.
  3. Another noteworthy trait is that the predictions precede the actual Bitcoin prices by at least few days. Unfortunately, we cannot know which variable contributed. It is remarkable nonetheless, for if we can forecast the trend of whether the Bitcoin price will go up or down, we can exploit this for money making.
